          "body": "The Lystra scene (14:8-18) is Luke's most concentrated portrait of the pagan religious imagination encountering apostolic miracle. When the lame man leaps up, the crowd's instinctive theological move is upward — *the gods have become like men* — and they reach for Zeus and Hermes (14:11-12). Ovid's *Metamorphoses* (8.626-724) preserves a local legend that Zeus and Hermes had once visited the area in human form and been refused hospitality by all but one elderly couple. The Lystrans had been culturally primed not to miss the gods a second time. Their reflex is the universal pagan reflex: to absorb the miraculous into existing categories rather than let it expose those categories as *vain things* (14:15). Paul and Barnabas tear their clothes — a gesture of horror at blasphemy (cf. Matt 26:65) — and rush into the crowd to refuse the worship. Verse 14 is one of the most morally luminous moments in Acts: apostles refusing the glory their gift had earned them."
