          "body": "Acts 14:15-17 is the New Testament's first recorded gospel address to pure pagans without Jewish substrate, and it functions as a homiletical bridge to the Areopagus sermon of Acts 17. Paul's structure is: (1) repudiate the false gods as *vain things* (*mataia*, the LXX's standard word for idols); (2) point to the *living God* who made heaven, earth, sea, and all that is in them — the Genesis 1 framework, not Sinai; (3) name God's past forbearance — *He permitted all the nations to go their own ways* — without softening it into approval; (4) name God's witness in providence — rain, fruitful seasons, food, gladness. The Lystran natural theology is real but insufficient; it is enough to render pagans accountable (Rom 1:18-21) but not enough to save. The sermon is cut short (14:18) before Paul reaches Christ, suggesting that Luke is giving us a homiletical *opening* — the foundation on which a fuller proclamation would build (cf. Acts 17:30-31, where the Areopagus speech completes the structure with repentance, judgment, and resurrection)."
