          "body": "*Through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God.* Three words bear the weight: *thlipsis* (tribulation, pressure), *dei* (it is necessary, divine must), and *basileia* (kingdom, the consummated reign). The verse is the chapter's interpretive key and one of Paul's most concentrated theological summaries. *Thlipsis* is not random suffering but the specific pressure that comes from gospel allegiance in a hostile world (cf. Rom 5:3; 8:35; 2 Cor 4:17; 1 Thess 3:3). *Dei* makes this necessity divine, not circumstantial — the same *dei* Jesus uses of His own suffering in Mark 8:31. *Basileia* is the future inheritance toward which present tribulations are the prescribed road. The verse is spoken to *new* disciples at Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch — the very cities where Paul has just been stoned, expelled, and threatened. Paul does not soften the message for fresh converts; he installs the doctrine of suffering at the foundation of their discipleship. Modern evangelism that promises freedom from tribulation is not the apostolic message."
